      "title": "<$n>) Dinner Scene",
      "description": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "That night, Pa came in from the fields. He smelled of cow shit mixed with unbathed stench baked into his skin from the hours toiling in the blazing Arizona sun. As soon as he slammed the front door, he saw the setting for Bee at the dinner table. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I held my breath. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He glared at me as he smashed the extra plate against the wall."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Ma stood at the stove and stirred the sauce. I slipped between her and him. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"No way. You really is crazy if you think I’m putting up with this.\" He raised his hand and flung the back of it across my face. \"Now get me my dinner.\""
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Pa shoved meatloaf and mashed potatoes in his mouth, barely chewing, slopping gravy on his shirt. He gulped down his fourth beer. His belch announced he was done."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I heard you was working with Caroline Jones. We don’t accept charity. Tell her you won’t be coming by anymore,” pa said. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“It’s not charity. I work for her.” "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Ha! You’re too stupid to work for anybody. It’s charity. Besides you've got chores enough around here. Now give me whatever money she’s given you so far.” "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I glared at him. “I haven’t been paid yet.” I lied. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He squinted his eyes at me. “Yeah, well, don’t go back.” "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I opened my mouth to speak but his look kept me from talking. We finished our dinner in silence. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"One good thing, Bee don’t eat much, and from the looks of it neither do you,\" pa laughed, pushed back his chair, and stood. As he pass by me he whacked my head. \"Looks like you got some sweeping to do.\" He kicked part of the broken plate at my legs. He grabbed another beer, and plopped into his chair in front of the TV. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I slid some meatloaf and rolls into my apron pocket for Bee, then took the dishes to the sink where ma was washing. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Why do you make trouble, Suzie? You know Bee don’t sit at the table when he’s home,\" Ma whispered. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"But it's not right.\""
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Stop, now, before you get us another beating.\" She soaked her hands in the soapy water and lowered her eyes. \"I can’t take much more.\""
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"It’s okay, ma. We don’t need him. We don’t need nobody.\" "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Ma shook her head and went back to washing dishes. \"You seem to need Bee,\" Ma said without looking up."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " I spent the rest of the night in my bedroom with the door closed. The meatloaf I snuck in didn't take long to disappear. Ma's words 'you seem to need Bee,' and Mrs. Jones's words, 'It isn't cute anymore,' and 'she's got to accept the truth' echoed in my head. I didn't need Bee, Bee needed me. If it weren't for me, she'd take the beatings from Pa, and wouldn't have a voice. She needed me, and I was nothing without her."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Add Pa telling Suzie she can't see Mrs. J again. "
                }
              ]
            },
