    {
      "id": 14,
      "lineId": 1,
      "beatId": 3,
      "bookId": 1,
      "positionWithinLine": 3,
      "positionInBeat": 2,
      "title": "<$n>) Pa is shot",
      "description": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Maybe Ma was born slow, or maybe the beatings helped it along, but some time after the third baby died she figured it out, probably more like finally admitted, that Pa had been doing Bee. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She asked him, \"You the daddy?\""
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " \"No,\" he said with dripping sarcasm. \"Maculate ’ceptions I suppose,\" he laughed, shaking his head. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Ma walked up to him. Face to face. Slapped him. I couldn’t believe it, I had never seen her stand up to him before. But he didn’t take kindly to it. He full-on punched her in the face. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She staggered back, blood poured from her nose."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Pa stomped out the front door, pushing the porch screen so hard it stuck open. An odd silence filled the room. Time seemed to stand still, and race all at once. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Pa's the daddy. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "When it sunk in, she wasn’t slow at all."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Ma reached behind the door. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Bang. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "The shotgun blasted. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Then stillness."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Pa’s body was on the ground, face down."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "My feet seemed bolted to the ground. I swapped glances between Ma’s bloody nose and Pa’s bleeding body. I felt Bee smile."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Without a word, Ma reloaded the shotgun and put it back behind the door where it’s kept. She took off her apron and wiped her bloody nose. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Don’t you worry. Everything is going to be alright,\" Ma said. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She went into the kitchen and picked up the phone. \""
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Bobby"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": ", I need you here, can you come right away?… No?\" She scurried about, tossing her apron in the wash after one last swipe to her nose. \"It’s important. Can you come soon?… One hour?… No sooner?… It’s really important, come as soon as you can.\" She hung up the phone. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Ma took a deep breath and smoothed her dress. \"Well, now. You hungry?\" Ma said. \"I’ll make breakfast.\""
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I couldn’t believe my ears. \"Shouldn’t we call 911 or something?"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"No need for 911. I’ll call the police after Bobby gets here.\" Ma put her arm around me. \"Now Suzie, what happened here, we cannot talk about it to anyone.\" Ma’s voice was stern. \"Anyone. Ever.\" "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I’d never heard her stern before. Her eyes probed me. A second later, a wave of recognition crashed in me. I didn't want Ma to be taken away. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I looked out at Pa, lying there. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Did he move?"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "True to her word, we had breakfast. The holiday kind of breakfast we have when other kin are around. Eggs, bacon, pancakes with homemade maple syrup. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Pa laid in the front yard. Shot. Long ago I had mourned the loss of my Pa, the Pa that didn’t beat us as much, or make babies with Bee. That Pa, he died eons ago. Yet, this rush of sadness flooded me."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Everything’s alright now,\" she said. \"No one’s ever going to hurt us, ever again.\" Ma began to clear the plates. Her head held higher, back straighter, eyes brighter. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"What we going to do today?\" asked Ma. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "My eyes darted between the front yard and this strange woman filled with confidence and unrelenting action. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Don’t you worry about the mess, pumpkin,\" she said. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "The dishes, or Pa? Should we go see about Pa?"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " Bee’s mouth looked like a fly trap, awaiting its prey. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I sat back down. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"So?\" Ma smiled. \"I know. Let’s picnic! We can fetch the fattest chicken, fry ‘em crispy, and make some potato salad. We’ll pack it all up and go down by the lake. How does that sound?\" "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I tried to talk but nothing came out on the count of I was still thinking of Pa in the front yard."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Bee sat up a little straighter. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Why, that’s the spirit! Now Suzie, doesn’t your Bee deserve a fun day. What ya say? You good?\" "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Maybe they were right––maybe we's all crazy. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Uh. Sure,\" I mumbled. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Wonderful! Now how about you finish up here and start getting that chicken ready for our picnic. As soon as Uncle Bobby gets here, I’m goin’ out a piece, but I be back, and we’ll head out.\" "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"You’re leaving?\" "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She started to raise her hands. I stiffened. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Tears filled her eyes. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Oh, sweetie. I’m just reaching to hug you. You don’t ever have to be scared again.\" "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She cupped my face with her hands, pulled me in and kissed my cheek. The shooting did something to her. Ma was different. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Bobby pulled up in his Chevy truck, stopping feet from where Pa lay. He rushed out of the car to David’s side. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"What the hell? Who did this?\" Bobby kneeled next to David. His hand started to touch him, then he pulled it back just as quick."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Thank god you’re here,\" Susan said to her brother. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Christ, Susan.\" Bobby jumped to his feet and stood face to face with her. Part of him wanted to hit her, the part that knew David was the closest thing he had to a friend. Another part of him was glad he was dead: David never deserved this land, his land. David wasn’t even a farmer. The sweat beaded on his forehead, his jaw clench. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Susan fixed her stare. \"You. Owe. Me.\" "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "The words didn’t register at first. Then it hit him. It was so long ago he had figured she’d never call in her chip. Damnit. Damnit. Damnit. Memories of the street whore’s battered face and lifeless body flashed before his eyes."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "His face went slack. This would be the second dead body they’d moved. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "\"Okay, then.\" Susan took a breath. \"I’ll get the truck.\" "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Bobby stood there. Stunned. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Need to make Suzie older sounding "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "** Add info on shovel handle "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Ma realized Pa is the daddy of the three stillborn children, ***add what made Ma realized, and next thing Pa is shot. Unclear as to who did it. Ma believes Pa is dead, calls her bother Bobby to help clean up.*** Add in shovel info ***Suzie should see Bobby and Ma aruguing before they drive off (arguing about what to do since he isn't dead yet. \n"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
